She asked if Fair housing set the deadline  EP said yes but that because the deadline had passed  there was nothing we could do and no exceptions could be made. She asked if her house was on fire  is there still nothing we could do. EP said that is not the case here. EP suggested that Ms. Stram sign up for the BRA email list so that she can be notified immediately for the next opportunities. Ms. Stram was concerned that if she was on the list  then she may be penalized for turning other opportunities down if they are in undesirable areas. EP explained that it is only an email list to alert her as to the opportunities and that she would have to apply to the ones she is interested in. Closed date : 2016-03-04 17:44:31.267 Case Noted response to cconst from APCC: Dear Mr. Tydorowski:   The APCC has already checked it out and has been working with all parties involved (Building Consultant  Synergy Investment  Eversource and\xef\xbf\xbdSunbelt\xef\xbf\xbd(Generators Rental Company).\xef\xbf\xbd As you probably knew already  there was a fire at 100 Milk Street  and all electrical equipment were destroyed in the fire.\xef\xbf\xbd The generator(s) are there to provide electricity to the building while the building owner and Eversource are in the process of rebuilding and replacing all electrical equipment. \xef\xbf\xbd   Sunbelt\xef\xbf\xbdRentals has reached out to their exhaust specialist SOUNDEX to try to have them engineer a quick exhaust sound attenuator solution for the exhaust to help mitigate the operating noise of the machine at 10 Post Office Square.\xef\xbf\xbd They have secured a sound attenuator on a rush that will be shipped this week and they plan to get it installed hopefully by end of next week. \xef\xbf\xbdTypically this is something that would be heavily engineered but with such a short time frame we are looking at any and all solutions to help with the noise.     Sincerely      --\xef\xbf\xbd  Lugardy Raymond Environment Compliance Inspector City of Boston  The Environment Department Boston City Hall  Room 709 Tel:\xef\xbf\xbd(617) 635-3850 Fax:\xef\xbf\xbd(617) 635-3435 Email:\xef\xbf\xbdlugardy.raymond@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved National Grid is installing a new main on Beacon street. The city highly encourages this type of work. It will eliminate possible future emergency leak repairs.     The city acknowledges that the construction will cause an inconvenience to the residents.    However in the long run the construction is well worth it.     The City contacted National Grid and the contractor  directing them to always follow street closure proceedures (only with Police detail  notifying fire and MBTA).     In addition  we will ask them to leaflet Aberdeen St regarding the construction on Beacon St.     Any questions  you can call my office.     Sincerely      Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The No Stopping Signs posted at this location are corner restriction regulations.     This restriction was installed because it is a city ordinance not to park 20\' from an intersection and a complaint from residents from the neigborhood stated that there are visibility issues when pedestrians cross Academy Hill Rd (which is a two-way st) and fire apparatus have difficulty making a turn into Mt Vernon St.     Unforturnatley the section where the regulation has changed is only 30\' in length from Mt Vernon to the driveway leaving the no adequate space for a parking space.     This regulation has been installed for safety reasons at this location.     Thanking for your understanding.
